You can use `assert!`, `assert_eq!`, and similar macros for simple assertions, but for testing errors, you want to handle them properly. Suppose your function has an error that returns a `Result`. Here’s an example:

```rust
// src/lib.rs
pub fn divide(a: i32, b: i32) -> Result<i32, String> {
    if b == 0 {
        Err(String::from("Cannot divide by zero"))
    } else {
        Ok(a / b)
    }
}
```
And for the test:

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_divide_by_zero() {
        let result = divide(5, 0);
        assert_eq!(result.unwrap_err(), String::from("Cannot divide by zero"));
    }
}
```

